            <section class="mb-5">
                <p>
                    Short-term memory allows us to hold information in mind long enough to use it. It plays a
                    central role in everyday thinking, such as following instructions or keeping track of a task
                    as it unfolds. Rather than acting as a simple storage space, short-term memory helps maintain
                    and update information as we work with it. Because of this, it supports reasoning, learning,
                    and decision-making across many contexts (Baddeley, 2003; Cowan, 2010).
                </p>
                <p>
                    Modern work habits place steady demands on short-term memory, but they also reduce how often
                    it is used directly. Frequent interruptions, constant switching between tasks, and reliance
                    on reminders mean that fewer details need to be held in mind at once. Over time, this can
                    make it harder to keep information active without external support, especially during
                    multi-step or mentally demanding tasks.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="mb-5">
                <h2 class="h4 mb-3">How practice helps</h2>
                <p>
                    Research suggests that short-term memory is not fixed. Practice that requires briefly holding
                    and using information can improve performance on related tasks (Klingberg, 2010; Shipstead,
                    Redick, &amp; Engle, 2012). Well-designed exercises challenge this system in manageable ways.
                    They encourage active maintenance rather than simple repetition.
                </p>
                <p>
                    These exercises are not about memorising facts or pushing capacity to its limits. The goal is
                    to strengthen the ability to keep information available long enough to work with it. By
                    practising short, focused memory tasks, you are supporting a cognitive function that underlies
                    clear thinking in many areas of life.
                </p>
                <p>
                    To get the most out of these exercises, read the passage slowly, and only once.
                </p>
            </section>

